added opt-in callback and got recipientId.

The app still tries to send to Facebook after 1 second, even if it hasn’t gotten the optin yet, for the demo.  But, at least this give Facebook plenty of time to process the user's opt-in request.  The delay is 0, polling the db every 0.1 seconds for the optin.  I used a test library, Spock, for PollingConditions, because I don’t know offhand of a similar non-test library.

To get the optin callback, the Facebook app needs to be subscribed to it, by selecting the “messaging_optins” field on its webhooks config.

This saves the recipientId in the db, for sending messages in the future, as the nonce may only work once.  I changed the Volunteer.recipientId from Long to String, so this will require a db reset on Heroku.

This included moving the views/index.gsp to views/volunteer/create.gsp, and replacing the sample input fields with the relevant part of create.gsp.  It’s still displayed at the lowest index via an internal forward, but from the VolunteerController to support server-side validation (e.g., disallowing duplicate email addresses), although most such validation should be done on the client side.

implemented webhook to allow config of Facebook Messenger app

as described at https://developers.facebook.com/docs/messenger-platform/guides/quick-start

This uses an environment variable that I configured on my Heroku instance of this app as follows:

$ heroku config:set FACEBOOK_MESSENGER_VERIFY_TOKEN=XXX

where XXX is the Verify Token that I have configured for my Facebook app's Messenger added product's Webhooks config.  With this, I will see if Facebook will verify and save https://guarded-atoll-72753.herokuapp.com/webhook as my Callback URL.  (Facebook has rejected that URL so far, because of bad responses.)
